'''HIGH COTTON'''

Southern term used to reflect the best of times; a time of elation.  The term originates from the rural farming community in the antebellum (pre-Civil War era) when "high cotton" meant that the crops were good and the prices, likewise, were better.  It is commonly used in conjunction with several phrases such as "We're in high cotton now" or "You're in high cotton", meaning all is going very well.